Subject: MQS Reconciliation Observation – Significant Increase in Records Missing from Source CSV After 14 Apr Logic Change

Hi Team,

As part of the RadarLive MQS reconciliation analysis, we have been comparing the Athena source CSV against the downstream MQS flow using both:

Forward reconciliation → CSV records missing in MQS flow
Reverse reconciliation → MQS flow records missing in source CSV

After implementing the updated reverse reconciliation logic to correctly identify records present in MQS but absent in the CSV, we observed a significant discrepancy on the source side.

Key Observation

The reverse reconciliation results indicate that a large volume of records are present in the MQS flow but are not being included in the Athena source CSV extract.

This issue appears to have increased noticeably after the source-side logic change introduced around 14 Apr, which was intended to improve identification of records for the CSV extraction.

Based on the analysis, the updated logic may now be excluding additional valid MQS records from the CSV generation process.

Current Findings
Forward reconciliation % remains consistently high (~99.9%), indicating most CSV records are successfully reaching MQS.
However, Reverse reconciliation % has reduced significantly, proving the issue is primarily on the source CSV generation side rather than MQS ingestion.

From the latest analysis:

MQS flow volume is substantially higher than the CSV volume
Missing records in CSV have increased sharply from April onward
The gap continues to grow over time
